To determine the equations of motion for a Double Atwood machine, we need to consider the system's dynamics. In this setup, one of the pulleys in a standard Atwood machine is replaced by another Atwood machine. We'll denote the masses involved as \( m_1 \), \( m_2 \), and \( m_3 \), where \( m_1 \) and \( m_2 \) are the masses on the first Atwood machine, and \( m_3 \) is the mass on the second Atwood machine. We will also assume that the pulleys are massless and frictionless.

Here is the LaTeX code for the equations of motion:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Equations of Motion for a Double Atwood Machine}

Consider a Double Atwood machine where one of the pulleys is replaced by another Atwood machine. We denote the masses as follows:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( m_1 \) and \( m_2 \) are the masses on the first Atwood machine.
    \item \( m_3 \) is the mass on the second Atwood machine.
\end{itemize}

Assuming the pulleys are massless and frictionless, we can write the equations of motion based on Newton's second law.

For the first Atwood machine, the net force and acceleration \( a_1 \) can be expressed as:
\begin{equation}
(m_2 - m_1)g = (m_1 + m_2)a_1
\end{equation}

For the second Atwood machine, which is connected to the first, the net force and acceleration \( a_2 \) are given by:
\begin{equation}
(m_3 - m_2)g = (m_2 + m_3)a_2
\end{equation}

Here, \( g \) is the acceleration due to gravity. The accelerations \( a_1 \) and \( a_2 \) are related through the constraints of the system, which depend on the specific setup and connections between the masses.

\end{document}
```

This LaTeX code sets up the framework for analyzing the Double Atwood machine. The equations of motion are derived from Newton's second law, considering the constraints and relationships between the different parts of the system.

